	    <h1>Python and Tools</h1>
	    <article class="tutorial-panel">
		<h2>Python</h2>
		<ul>
		    <li>A <strong>general-purpose programming language</strong>, Python is <strong>high-level</strong> and <strong>interpreted</strong></li>
		    <li>Invented in the 1980s by Guido van Rossum in the Netherlands</li>
		    <li>It has specialised libraries for different applications, the most important ones for data analysis being <strong>Numpy</strong>, <strong>Matplotlib</strong> and <strong>Pandas</strong></li>
		</ul>
		
	    </article>
	    <article class="tutorial-panel">
		<h2>The tools</h2>
		<p>To work with Python, we will be using <strong>Jupyter Notebooks</strong>, which allow seamless combination of text and code, making them an apt tool for data analysis.</p>
		<dl>
		    <dt>In-class:</dt>
		    <dl>We will be using Jupyter Notebooks <a href="https://notebooks.azure.com/">on Azure</a>.<br/><br/>
			As a student in TU Dublin Tallaght Campus, you have a Microsoft account that you can use to log into Azure Notebooks. Your credentials are:
			<ul>
			    <li>username: &lt;your student id i.e. x-number>@computing.stu.it-tallaght.ie</li>
			    <li>password: &lt;your TU Dublin password></li>
			</ul>
		    </dl>
		    <dt>At home:</dt>
		    <dl>You may use Azure Notebooks or install Jupyter Notebook from PyCharm, as explained <a href="https://www.jetbrains.com/help/pycharm/using-ipython-notebook-with-product.html">here</a>.</dl>
		</dl>
